  "response": "The first touchscreen phone was the **IBM Simon Personal Communicator**, which was invented by **IBM** in the United States. It was developed in **1992** and released to the public in **1994**. The IBM Simon is considered the first smartphone because it combined the functions of a mobile phone with PDA (Personal Digital Assistant) features, such as a calendar, address book, and email capabilities. It featured a resistive touchscreen that allowed users to interact with the device using a stylus or their fingers. \n\nAlthough it was groundbreaking, the IBM Simon was not a commercial success due to its high price and limited battery life, but it laid the foundation for future touchscreen smartphones.",
